    • evenlyDivisible

      public static java.lang.String evenlyDivisible​(int a, int b)
      Write a static method to determine if a number x is evenly divisible by a number y. if x divided by y has no remainder. Two numbers are evenly divisible if either is evenly divisible by the other. Thus, 15 and 3 are evenly divisible, and 4 and 16 are evenly divisible, whereas 16 and 3 are not, and 8 and 0 are not. evenlyDivisible that accepts two integer parameters and returns string value

      For example: 

       if x= 10 and y =5 then return "10 and 5 are evenly divisible"
 if x= 4 and y =32  then return "4 and 32 are evenly divisible"
 if x= 0 and y=0  then return "Invalid input"
 if x =17 and y =4 then return "17 and 4 are NOT evenly divisible"
      Parameters:
      a - : int input value
      b - : int input value
      Returns:
      String value see above

    • isCongruent

      public static java.lang.String isCongruent​(int a, int b, int m)

      Modular Arithmetic

      Definition: If a and b are integers and m is a positive integer, then a is congruent to b modulo m if m divides a-b .

      In the other words, two integers are congruent mod m if and only if they have the same remainder when divided by m .

        Example:
  
  isCongruent ( 81,199,5) returns "81 and 199 NOT congruent modulo 5"
  isCongruent ( -8,8, 5) returns "-8 and 8 NOT congruent modulo 5"
  isCongruent ( 24, 14, 6) returns "24 and 14 NOT congruent modulo 6"
  isCongruent ( 10, 26, 8) returns "10 and 26 congruent modulo 8" 
  isCongruent ( 17, 5, 6) returns "17 and 5 congruent modulo 6"
  isCongruent ( -1,1, 2) returns "-1 and 1 congruent modulo 2" 
  isCongruent ( -8,2, 5) returns "-8 and 2 congruent modulo 5" 
  isCongruent ( 38,23, 15) returns "38 and 23 congruent modulo 15"
      Parameters:
      a - integer not equal to zero
      b - integer not equal to zero
      m - integer not equal to zero
      Returns:
      String value See above
      Precondition:
      m > 0 , a != 0 , b != 0

    • isPrime

      public static java.lang.String isPrime​(int n)

      Primes

      A positive integer n > 1 is called prime if the only positive factors of n are 1 and n . A positive integer that is greater than one and is not prime is called composite.

      An integer n is composite if and only if there exists an integer a such that a divides n and 1 < a < n.

      Hint: 1 is neither prime nor composite. It forms its own special category as a "unit".

      This method checks the positive integer if it is prime or not.

        Example:
  
  isPrime ( -5) returns "-5 is NOT Prime" 
  isPrime ( 6) returns "6 is NOT Prime" 
  isPrime ( 25) returns "25 is NOT Prime" 
  isPrime ( 2) returns "2 is Prime"  
  isPrime ( 3) returns "3 is Prime"  
  isPrime ( 13) returns "13 is Prime"  
  isPrime ( 17) returns "17 is Prime"  
  isPrime ( 29) returns "29 is Prime"
      Parameters:
      n - positive integer
      Returns:
      String value see above
      Precondition:
      n > 0
